00:05:53.610 --> 00:05:57.059
such as implicit headings,
insufficient color contrast,

00:05:57.480 --> 00:05:59.760
and images with improper alt text.

00:06:00.960 --> 00:06:06.599
I hope that you will be able to determine
how to approach remediating plugin-level

00:06:06.600 --> 00:06:08.040
or theme-level issues.

00:06:08.520 --> 00:06:11.219
Those ones can be more complicated,
so by the end of our talk today,

00:06:11.220 --> 00:06:15.450
you might not feel totally like you know
how to do it exactly,

00:06:15.660 --> 00:06:18.239
but you should have a sense of,
"All right, this is how I can go about it.

00:06:18.240 --> 00:06:19.520
This is how I would get started.

00:06:19.559 --> 00:06:20.974
This is how I could approach it."

00:06:26.910 --> 00:06:29.610
The main parts of a WordPress site,
I would say,

00:06:29.639 --> 00:06:30.869
are WordPress core,

00:06:31.379 --> 00:06:35.009
your theme and any customizations
that you've installed to it,

00:06:35.789 --> 00:06:37.470
any plugins that you've installed,

00:06:38.130 --> 00:06:41.340
your pages and your posts,
and your media library.

00:06:41.759 --> 00:06:44.728
The media library typically is
a collection of photos

00:06:44.729 --> 00:06:47.218
on your WordPress site,
but it can include other things as well,

00:06:47.219 --> 00:06:49.200
such as documents or videos.

00:06:50.550 --> 00:06:53.699
Now, to fix an accessibility issue
in WordPress,

00:06:54.059 --> 00:06:58.140
you need to start by identifying
where exactly the issue comes from.

00:06:58.979 --> 00:07:00.570
Is it specific to your theme?

00:07:00.599 --> 00:07:02.850
Is it a problem with your theme
and how you've set it up,

00:07:03.510 --> 00:07:06.089
or is it maybe specific
to a plugin you're using,

00:07:06.780 --> 00:07:09.659
or is it just
a page-level issue, for example?

00:07:13.170 --> 00:07:15.182
We're going to go
through these categories one by one.

00:07:15.183 --> 00:07:17.428
We're going to focus on pages,
and then plugins,

00:07:17.429 --> 00:07:18.429
and then themes.

00:07:18.840 --> 00:07:21.329
We'll talk about what types
of issues you can expect

00:07:21.330 --> 00:07:24.420
to find at each level
and how to go about fixing them.

00:07:26.790 --> 00:07:27.929
For this presentation,

00:07:28.079 --> 00:07:31.440
I'm going to focus on classic themes
instead of block themes,

00:07:32.039 --> 00:07:35.010
but some of what we talk about
will apply to those ones as well.

00:07:36.870 --> 00:07:39.569
I should note
that it won't always be perfectly clear

00:07:39.570 --> 00:07:43.019
at first where exactly an issue
comes from on a WordPress site,

00:07:43.379 --> 00:07:47.159
but we can make informed guesses,
and if you're an admin,

00:07:47.190 --> 00:07:50.430
you can log into that admin dashboard,
the back end,

00:07:50.820 --> 00:07:53.758
and poke around to figure out
where exactly an issue comes

00:07:53.759 --> 00:07:55.139
from and how to fix it.

00:07:56.790 --> 00:07:59.746
Here, I'll also note that if you're
a third-party consultant who's testing

00:07:59.849 --> 00:08:01.946
a site or even just testing your own site,

00:08:02.640 --> 00:08:06.419
when you report accessibility issues
on a WordPress site,

00:08:06.659 --> 00:08:07.659
I'd recommend

00:08:07.950 --> 00:08:10.084
that you include a likely source field

00:08:10.085 --> 00:08:12.840
so that for each accessibility issue
you flag,

00:08:13.110 --> 00:08:16.439
I think it can be helpful to note
where you think the issue is coming from.

00:08:17.220 --> 00:08:19.258
For example,
is it something you see repeated

00:08:19.259 --> 00:08:20.460
across multiple pages?

00:08:21.100 --> 00:08:23.220
In that case, it might be
a theme-level issue,

00:08:23.789 --> 00:08:27.089
but if the issue looks like it's specific
just to this one blog post,

00:08:27.359 --> 00:08:29.909
it might be a post or a page-level issue.

00:08:31.709 --> 00:08:34.109
If you want to go above and beyond,
you could maybe even get

00:08:34.110 --> 00:08:36.840
a list of the plugins
that are used on a site,

00:08:37.200 --> 00:08:41.369
and then take a guess as to which plugin
might be causing the issue,

00:08:41.370 --> 00:08:42.930
if you think it's a plugin-level issue.

00:08:43.080 --> 00:08:48.510
For example, if there's a plugin
that is installed for tabs or accordions,

00:08:48.539 --> 00:08:50.578
and you notice there's an issue
with tabs or accordions,

00:08:50.579 --> 00:08:52.109
it might be specific to that plugin.

00:08:53.580 --> 00:08:58.169
Now, if you're a site owner and you have
your accessibility issues sorted by type

00:08:58.170 --> 00:08:59.170
in this way,

00:08:59.459 --> 00:09:02.459
it might be able to help you speed
things along when you're trying

00:09:02.460 --> 00:09:05.159
to fix them. For example,
you can take all of your issues

00:09:05.160 --> 00:09:07.859
that look like they're related
to your theme and then send it

00:09:07.860 --> 00:09:10.680
to your theme developer
to work on fixing them,

00:09:11.010 --> 00:09:13.919
but if you have a lot of issues
that are really page-level issues,

00:09:14.459 --> 00:09:16.978
you can probably have
your content creators fix most of those

00:09:16.979 --> 00:09:21.088
because those are things
that content creators should be able

00:09:21.089 --> 00:09:23.249
to fix and should know
about when they're creating

00:09:23.279 --> 00:09:24.960
additional content for your site.

00:09:27.869 --> 00:09:30.299
With all that,
let's really dive into it and talk

00:09:30.300 --> 00:09:33.930
about page-level accessibility issues
you might find on a WordPress site.

00:09:39.149 --> 00:09:41.340
Page-level issues may include

00:09:41.880 --> 00:09:44.310
implicit or unnecessary headings.

00:09:45.118 --> 00:09:47.909
That means you have a heading
that is logically a heading,

00:09:47.910 --> 00:09:50.100
but it isn't programmatically marked
as such,

00:09:50.459 --> 00:09:51.479
or maybe the opposite,

00:09:51.480 --> 00:09:53.579
you have something
that is not logically a heading,

00:09:53.580 --> 00:09:55.410
but you've actually tagged it
as a heading.

00:09:56.550 --> 00:09:59.249
Related, another page-level issue
might be implicit list,

00:09:59.250 --> 00:10:02.219
which is you have a list,
but it isn't programmatically marked

00:10:02.220 --> 00:10:03.220
as a list.

00:10:04.110 --> 00:10:06.750
These issues are important
for screen reader users mostly

00:10:06.779 --> 00:10:10.108
because they can navigate your page
by jumping to headings or jumping

00:10:10.109 --> 00:10:11.109
to list items.

00:10:11.520 --> 00:10:12.593
Also, if you don't have

00:10:12.869 --> 00:10:15.371
a heading tagged as a heading,
it might be confusing to a user

00:10:15.372 --> 00:10:17.590
who doesn't realize
that it's a heading for a section.

00:10:19.282 --> 00:10:22.929
Other page-level issues could include
insufficient color contrast,

00:10:23.529 --> 00:10:25.869
but just for particular blocks of text.

00:10:26.080 --> 00:10:28.869
Sometimes color contrast issues
are theme-level issues.

00:10:28.870 --> 00:10:31.899
If you see it
across multiple pages on your site,

00:10:32.110 --> 00:10:33.999
or if you see it,
for example, in your footer,

00:10:34.329 --> 00:10:36.310
that's probably more
of a theme-level issue,

00:10:36.580 --> 00:10:38.348
but if it's just
a particular block of text

00:10:38.349 --> 00:10:41.649
on one particular page,
that's probably a page-level issue.

00:10:42.963 --> 00:10:47.228
Another page-level issue could be images
on that page that are missing

00:10:47.229 --> 00:10:50.559
alternative text or that have
inappropriate alt text.

00:10:54.520 --> 00:10:56.499
I'm going to switch
over from my PowerPoint here

00:10:57.220 --> 00:10:59.919
to an actual WordPress site,
and we're going to look

00:10:59.920 --> 00:11:02.200
at some specific page-level issues.

00:11:03.729 --> 00:11:07.269
I'm going to scroll down this page,
and I want you to think about what

00:11:07.270 --> 00:11:11.350
are some types of issues
that either you spot or that you think,

00:11:11.710 --> 00:11:13.990
"Hey, I think that might be
a page-level issue.

00:11:14.469 --> 00:11:16.330
That's something I'd want
to investigate more."

00:11:18.039 --> 00:11:20.103
I'm going
to give you about 30 seconds for that.

00:11:54.461 --> 00:11:58.270
<v Cam> All right. I'm going to briefly go
over the page-level issues on this page.

00:11:58.479 --> 00:12:01.330
First up, you may have noticed
we have some text here

00:12:01.510 --> 00:12:03.309
that has very low color contrast.

00:12:04.239 --> 00:12:06.580
It's a light gray text
against a white background.

00:12:06.939 --> 00:12:09.866
You might not have even noticed it
because it's quite hard to see.

00:12:09.867 --> 00:12:11.827
I'm going to highlight it here
in case that helps.

00:12:11.952 --> 00:12:14.258
It says, "These black beans
are so delicious and easy to make.

00:12:14.259 --> 00:12:15.490
You're going to love them."

00:12:15.491 --> 00:12:18.695
This is a page-type issue.
It's a recipe,

00:12:20.590 --> 00:12:21.938
so that's one page-level issue.

00:12:21.939 --> 00:12:24.160
This text has very bad color contrast.

00:12:24.639 --> 00:12:27.040
Right below that, we have
an image of black beans,

00:12:27.400 --> 00:12:29.649
and I'm going to go ahead
and inspect this element.

00:12:32.679 --> 00:12:37.149
You can see that over here
in the accessibility pane within DevTools,

00:12:37.420 --> 00:12:41.799
it says, "Image has empty alt text,"
which is not something you would want.

00:12:41.800 --> 00:12:45.428
This is a page for a recipe,

00:12:45.429 --> 00:12:48.700
so you probably want to be able to know
what the food actually looks like.

00:12:49.450 --> 00:12:51.951
In this case, I think we want
to make sure that image has alt text.

00:12:51.952 --> 00:12:53.980
so that's another page-level issue here.

00:12:55.120 --> 00:12:56.439
Then just below that,

00:12:56.440 --> 00:13:00.069
we have the heading ingredients,
which proceeds a list of ingredients.

00:13:01.029 --> 00:13:02.200
When I inspect this,

00:13:05.019 --> 00:13:08.258
you'll see that this is just
a paragraph element with a strong element

00:13:08.259 --> 00:13:09.259
nested inside of it.

00:13:09.430 --> 00:13:12.379
It is not programmatically
or logically a heading,

00:13:12.854 --> 00:13:14.258
so that's an issue as well.

00:13:14.259 --> 00:13:17.229
Again, for screen reader users,
they won't know that it's a heading,

00:13:17.259 --> 00:13:19.450
and it'll be harder for them
to navigate the page.

00:13:21.189 --> 00:13:22.569
How do we go about fixing these?

00:13:25.480 --> 00:13:26.844
Let me check my notes.

00:13:28.649 --> 00:13:31.157
Cool, yes.
To fix a page-level issue,

00:13:32.409 --> 00:13:35.469
you can come to the WordPress backend,
the admin dashboard,

00:13:35.770 --> 00:13:37.658
and then you're going to want
to navigate to that page.

00:13:37.659 --> 00:13:39.219
In this case, I'm going to go to Pages,

00:13:39.729 --> 00:13:40.729
All pages,

00:13:41.919 --> 00:13:43.773
and then I'll select the page title.

00:13:44.742 --> 00:13:47.229
That'll take me
to the WordPress block editor

00:13:47.230 --> 00:13:48.447
for this page.

00:13:50.919 --> 00:13:54.569
The way you fix most page-level issues
is through the WordPress block editor.

00:13:54.570 --> 00:13:58.236
For example, I'm going to navigate
to this block of text that has

00:13:58.237 --> 00:13:59.638
a very low color contrast.

00:14:01.158 --> 00:14:04.239
Then over here
on the right side of my screen,

00:14:04.480 --> 00:14:08.799
you'll see that there's a pane
for the current block that's selected,

00:14:09.190 --> 00:14:10.899
a little tab control there.

00:14:11.200 --> 00:14:12.880
Right below that,
it says it's a paragraph.

00:14:13.299 --> 00:14:16.413
Then there's a section for color,
for the text color of this block.

00:14:17.097 --> 00:14:20.293
You'll actually see WordPress
will usually warn you if text has

00:14:20.295 --> 00:14:22.330
insufficient color contrast,
which is great.

00:14:22.839 --> 00:14:26.739
Here it says, "This color combination
may be hard for people to read.

00:14:27.070 --> 00:14:30.669
Try using
a brighter background color and/or

00:14:30.880 --> 00:14:32.229
a darker text color."

00:14:34.329 --> 00:14:38.230
That's one notice that this actually
is a problem, which is great.

00:14:38.650 --> 00:14:44.799
To change this, I'll just select
the text color here, sorry, one sec,

00:14:46.359 --> 00:14:47.920
and then I can choose a new color.

00:14:48.700 --> 00:14:52.029
In this case, I can just click on black
to change that text color to black,

00:14:52.659 --> 00:14:54.160
and that'll do it,

00:14:54.190 --> 00:14:56.679
so now you can see this text
has much better color contrast.

00:14:57.037 --> 00:15:00.070
That's one way you can fix
color contrast issues on the page-level.

00:15:01.029 --> 00:15:03.550
Next up, I'm going to skip down
to the heading next.

00:15:04.239 --> 00:15:06.405
I'll click on this heading
for Ingredients.

00:15:07.120 --> 00:15:10.358
You'll see, if you look again under
the block pane,

00:15:10.359 --> 00:15:13.173
under the block tab here, it says,
"This is just a paragraph,"

00:15:13.174 --> 00:15:14.589
but this actually should be set

00:15:14.590 --> 00:15:17.938
as not a paragraph block,
but a heading block.

00:15:18.679 --> 00:15:23.169
To change that, I'm going to navigate
to the toolbar for this block,

00:15:23.740 --> 00:15:26.349
and over here on the left,
start of this toolbar,

00:15:26.380 --> 00:15:28.030
there's a button titled Paragraph.

00:15:28.479 --> 00:15:30.519
When I click on that,
it'll open this little pop up,

00:15:31.029 --> 00:15:34.210
and I have options to transform
this to another type of block.

00:15:34.660 --> 00:15:36.280
In this case, I will select Heading.

00:15:39.760 --> 00:15:41.229
That is not quite working.

00:15:41.379 --> 00:15:43.360
I think I need to just try one more time.

00:15:52.179 --> 00:15:55.043
Okay, there we go.
I've set that as a heading now.

00:15:56.679 --> 00:15:59.289
Now you can see again,
under block on the right sidebar,

00:15:59.833 --> 00:16:01.989
it actually identifies
that as a heading block.

00:16:02.859 --> 00:16:04.838
You want to make sure your headings
are appropriate levels.

00:16:04.839 --> 00:16:06.070
Again, in the toolbar,

00:16:06.459 --> 00:16:09.569
for WordPress, there's a control
for change level.

00:16:09.570 --> 00:16:11.104
It has this icon H2.

00:16:11.470 --> 00:16:13.479
If you select that,
you can change it to a heading one,

00:16:13.480 --> 00:16:14.709
heading two, or heading three.

00:16:15.009 --> 00:16:17.649
In this case, a heading two makes
sense, so we'll leave it at that,

00:16:18.100 --> 00:16:20.349
and that's how you could fix
a heading level issue

00:16:20.350 --> 00:16:23.410
in the WordPress block editor
for a specific page.

00:16:24.339 --> 00:16:25.899
Next up, let's look at this photo here.

00:16:26.619 --> 00:16:30.255
When I select this photo again
in the block toolbar here,

00:16:30.880 --> 00:16:32.380
under settings,

00:16:32.560 --> 00:16:35.589
there's a field for alternative text,
and you can see that that's blank,

00:16:36.340 --> 00:16:37.380
which is not what we want.

00:16:37.930 --> 00:16:40.930
We want to make sure that this image
has good informative alternative text.

00:16:41.859 --> 00:16:44.109
In this case, before we do that,

00:16:44.110 --> 00:16:46.601
I'm going to back
out of the block editor for a moment.

00:16:46.602 --> 00:16:48.478
I'm going to click Save just for now.

00:16:50.834 --> 00:16:54.609
In the WordPress backend,
the dashboard here,

00:16:54.789 --> 00:16:56.439
I'm going to navigate to media,

00:16:56.470 --> 00:16:58.548
which is where you can find
photos on your site.

00:16:58.871 --> 00:17:02.199
I'm going to select this photo
that I had uploaded of black beans,

00:17:02.709 --> 00:17:06.518
and you can see there's a field here
for alternative text and also a field

00:17:06.519 --> 00:17:07.519
for description.

00:17:07.630 --> 00:17:08.630
Here, I added

00:17:08.859 --> 00:17:11.372
a small bowl of cooked
black beans beside a lime.

00:17:11.791 --> 00:17:14.359
That should actually be set
as the alternative text in this case

00:17:14.361 --> 00:17:17.818
so I'm going to copy that and paste it
into alternative text.

00:17:18.837 --> 00:17:23.260
Now, the next time I use this photo,
when I upload it again on another page,

00:17:23.349 --> 00:17:26.457
it'll have that as the default text,
which is awesome.

00:17:27.087 --> 00:17:29.967
Let's go back to the page we were looking
at and see how that affects it.

00:17:39.477 --> 00:17:42.426
When I navigate back to this image,
even though we just added

00:17:42.427 --> 00:17:45.549
alt text to it, you'll see that it still
doesn't have any alt text.

00:17:46.089 --> 00:17:48.289
That's actually, in some ways,
I would call it a feature

00:17:48.369 --> 00:17:51.820
because good alternative text
is contextual.

00:17:52.060 --> 00:17:54.999
The same image in different contexts,
you'll want to use

00:17:55.000 --> 00:17:56.110
different alt text for it.

00:17:56.650 --> 00:17:58.210
That's what WordPress is assuming here.

00:17:58.960 --> 00:18:01.032
If I were to add the image again,
my understanding is

00:18:01.033 --> 00:18:03.160
that I think it would use
the default alt text,

00:18:03.369 --> 00:18:07.147
but since I already have it on the page,
it thinks I don't want any alt text here.

00:18:07.148 --> 00:18:10.630
In this case, I can just paste
the alt text that I had earlier into here,

00:18:10.660 --> 00:18:13.570
but if I wanted to change it
to be more specific to this page,

00:18:13.689 --> 00:18:14.689
I could.

00:18:14.889 --> 00:18:16.599
One reason you might want
to do this, for example,

00:18:16.600 --> 00:18:19.687
is if you have
an image of a dog at a park,

00:18:19.749 --> 00:18:23.109
and if the topic of the page
is just talking about dogs in general

00:18:23.312 --> 00:18:25.627
for a bunch of people who own dogs,

00:18:25.628 --> 00:18:27.608
you might want to have
general alt text that says,

00:18:27.609 --> 00:18:29.488
"A golden retriever chases a ball,"

00:18:30.009 --> 00:18:32.800
but if it's for your personal blog
where you share about your life,

00:18:33.189 --> 00:18:35.989
in that case, you might want to describe
the dog by their name and say,

00:18:36.610 --> 00:18:39.388
"Koda chases a ball at a park."

00:18:41.428 --> 00:18:44.619
That's one reason you might want
to have alt text for different cases.

00:18:44.829 --> 00:18:46.329
In this case, we added the alt text here.

00:18:46.330 --> 00:18:48.208
I'm going to go ahead and hit Save.

00:18:49.179 --> 00:18:53.518
Then we'll navigate back to this page,
and I will refresh it.

00:18:54.988 --> 00:18:57.640
Now you can see this text
is much better color contrast.

00:18:58.120 --> 00:19:00.208
This heading, if we inspect it,

00:19:01.539 --> 00:19:04.539
it is programmatically marked
as a heading level two,

00:19:04.540 --> 00:19:05.788
which is great.

00:19:06.550 --> 00:19:08.179
If I inspect the image as well,

00:19:08.180 --> 00:19:11.168
you'll see that it now
has alt text for it.

00:19:12.789 --> 00:19:14.708
That would be an example
of how you can remediate

00:19:14.709 --> 00:19:17.199
some page-level accessibility issues
on WordPress.

00:19:17.590 --> 00:19:19.780
Ultimately, page-level issues
are things that you can,

00:19:19.960 --> 00:19:22.899
for the most part, fix
once you view the page here

00:19:22.900 --> 00:19:24.670
in the WordPress block editor.

00:19:25.090 --> 00:19:27.519
You want to make sure you're using
the proper block type,

00:19:27.789 --> 00:19:30.640
if it's a list or a heading
or a paragraph.

00:19:31.660 --> 00:19:36.349
You want to make sure you have
sufficient color contrast.

00:19:36.350 --> 00:19:39.790
Yes, that mostly covers it, so we're going
to have to move on from there.

00:19:41.589 --> 00:19:43.270
I'll jump back to our presentation.

00:19:49.120 --> 00:19:52.240
Next, we are going to talk
about plugin-level issues.

00:19:55.090 --> 00:19:57.699
Plugin-level issues are
the most, I would say,

00:19:57.789 --> 00:20:00.849
maybe complicated to remediate,
or at least the most complicated

00:20:00.850 --> 00:20:05.500
to figure out because plugins
do so many different things in WordPress.

00:20:06.099 --> 00:20:10.629
If a plugin adds a component to your site,
and if there's an accessibility issue

00:20:10.630 --> 00:20:14.799
with that component specifically,
it's probably a plugin-level issue.

00:20:14.979 --> 00:20:18.790
For example, if you wanted a tab control
on your site or an accordion,

00:20:18.819 --> 00:20:21.699
and if you add a plugin to do that,
and then if there is

00:20:21.700 --> 00:20:24.900
an accessibility issue with that,
it's probably from that plugin.

00:20:26.319 --> 00:20:29.799
I would recommend that you keep
your plugins as limited as possible

00:20:29.979 --> 00:20:33.190
and used for very specific purposes,
otherwise,

00:20:33.191 --> 00:20:37.420
it might be harder to identify
the exact source of plugin-level issues.

00:20:37.421 --> 00:20:42.550
If you have multiple plugins
for accordions,

00:20:42.552 --> 00:20:45.461
for example, or if you have
plugins that kind of overlap,

00:20:47.079 --> 00:20:51.070
so try to use as few plugins as possible,
have them for very clear purposes,

00:20:51.340 --> 00:20:52.629
and that'll help you identify,

00:20:52.630 --> 00:20:55.599
"Oh, there's an issue
with this specific thing on the site.

00:20:55.630 --> 00:20:58.328
We know that's related
to a plugin, so that's probably

00:20:58.329 --> 00:21:00.095
the source of this issue."

00:21:02.465 --> 00:21:06.254
Here, I'm going to jump
back to our test site

00:21:06.255 --> 00:21:08.045
and show you a plugin-level issue.

00:21:10.625 --> 00:21:15.790
On this page, I installed a plugin
for a tab control component.

00:21:16.079 --> 00:21:17.079
It's very simple.

00:21:17.080 --> 00:21:19.449
There's just two tabs called
first tab and second tab,

00:21:19.450 --> 00:21:22.779
and they both have
some lorem ipsum filler text in it.

00:21:24.460 --> 00:21:28.329
The issue with this tab component
is it's missing a visible focus indicator.

00:21:29.079 --> 00:21:32.349
I'm going to try to navigate this page
using the tab key for a moment.

00:21:34.089 --> 00:21:38.289
This is something that sighted users,
who have mobility challenges might do

00:21:38.290 --> 00:21:40.868
to navigate a site.
Rather than using a mouse,

00:21:40.869 --> 00:21:42.788
or a touchscreen,
they might use a keyboard

00:21:42.789 --> 00:21:45.400
or other types of assistive technology
that mimics a keyboard.

00:21:46.089 --> 00:21:48.099
In order to know
how to activate a control,

00:21:48.130 --> 00:21:50.199
they need to see
a visible focus indicator.

00:21:50.894 --> 00:21:53.229
Right now, you can see
there's this dotted outline

00:21:53.260 --> 00:21:55.120
around the one comment link,

00:21:55.810 --> 00:21:57.640
and so that indicates
that if I press Enter,

00:21:57.730 --> 00:21:59.439
that'll activate that control right now.

00:21:59.739 --> 00:22:01.330
That has a visible focus indicator,

00:22:01.899 --> 00:22:04.569
but when I press Tab to try
to navigate to the next control,

00:22:05.758 --> 00:22:06.758
there's nothing.

00:22:06.759 --> 00:22:09.698
There's no visible indicator
of what currently has keyboard focus,

00:22:09.699 --> 00:22:13.179
of what will be activated if I press Tab.
If I press Tab again,

00:22:13.840 --> 00:22:15.940
still no visible keyboard focus indicator.

00:22:16.899 --> 00:22:19.748
If I press it again, you'll see
this edit control at the bottom

00:22:19.749 --> 00:22:22.389
now does have a focus outline.

00:22:23.319 --> 00:22:26.379
That's what I would call
a plugin-level issue because I installed

00:22:26.380 --> 00:22:27.380
this plugin here

00:22:27.789 --> 00:22:29.050
for this tab control,

00:22:29.500 --> 00:22:33.369
and it's missing a focus indicator,
very clearly related to that.

00:22:35.050 --> 00:22:37.659
How do we go about fixing
these plugin-level issues?

00:22:41.950 --> 00:22:45.970
First, I would recommend make
sure you're using the plugin properly.

00:22:46.870 --> 00:22:51.070
If possible, you want to change
how that plugin or that specific component

00:22:51.099 --> 00:22:53.260
is configured to fix the issue.

00:22:54.069 --> 00:22:56.678
Some plugins are very simple
and don't give you a lot of options,

00:22:56.679 --> 00:22:58.300
but others are very complex.

00:22:59.169 --> 00:23:01.628
It might be possible to use
the plugin accessibly,

00:23:01.629 --> 00:23:04.509
but it might not be the default,
which is unfortunate,

00:23:04.510 --> 00:23:06.640
but it is often the case
with a lot of plugins,

00:23:06.970 --> 00:23:09.069
that if you configure it
in a particular way,

00:23:09.129 --> 00:23:11.169
it'll be accessible,
but the default is not.

00:23:11.830 --> 00:23:14.770
First, make sure you've configured it
in the best possible way,

00:23:14.799 --> 00:23:17.378
you've looked
over all of the options, and also make

00:23:17.379 --> 00:23:19.060
sure you've checked out
some documentation.

00:23:19.634 --> 00:23:22.900
Larger plugins will have documentation
about how to get it set up

00:23:23.620 --> 00:23:26.078
and used properly, so make
sure you give that a read over.

00:23:26.079 --> 00:23:30.368
It very well might be possible to fix
your plugin-level issues just by changing

00:23:30.369 --> 00:23:32.199
how you have configured your plugin.

00:23:32.770 --> 00:23:36.640
This is going to vary a lot
depending on what the actual issue is

00:23:36.790 --> 00:23:38.019
and what plugin you're using.

00:23:39.640 --> 00:23:42.999
Now, if that doesn't work,
and if it's a CSS-level issues,

00:23:43.449 --> 00:23:48.070
you can try adding custom CSS
in the additional CSS panel

00:23:48.520 --> 00:23:50.590
within the theme customizer,

00:23:51.160 --> 00:23:53.441
and I'm going to show you
how to do this in just a minute.

00:23:53.920 --> 00:23:57.259
Actually, we should show you now,
and then we'll come back.

00:23:57.260 --> 00:24:03.250
CSS-level issues typically result
in low color contrast,

00:24:03.729 --> 00:24:09.608
or we're just looking at a lack
of a visible keyboard focus indicator

00:24:09.609 --> 00:24:11.409
is also a CSS-level issues.

00:24:12.310 --> 00:24:14.040
Let's look at how we might fix that one.

00:24:15.040 --> 00:24:16.830
Here I'm going to inspect this code,

00:24:17.460 --> 00:24:25.300
this tab control in Chrome DevTools,
and I'm going to filter for Focus styles.

00:24:26.859 --> 00:24:32.049
You'll see that there is this one CSS rule
here that says it does actually have

00:24:32.050 --> 00:24:34.358
an outline,
but it's a transparent outline,

00:24:34.359 --> 00:24:36.399
so you don't see it, which is not great.

00:24:36.640 --> 00:24:38.949
What I'm going to do is I'm going
to copy this CSS rule,

00:24:39.939 --> 00:24:41.560
and then in the WordPress backend,

00:24:42.879 --> 00:24:44.140
I'm going to navigate

00:24:45.130 --> 00:24:46.210
to appearance,

00:24:46.780 --> 00:24:48.130
and then customize.

00:24:52.479 --> 00:24:55.719
Then on this next page,
I'll navigate down to additional CSS

00:24:55.720 --> 00:24:57.550
in this left side bar with options,

00:24:58.750 --> 00:25:01.359
and here I can add
additional CSS to the site.

00:25:01.839 --> 00:25:05.080
I'm going to paste
that CSS rule that I had copied,

00:25:06.160 --> 00:25:08.019
and I'm going to change
that to something new,

00:25:08.049 --> 00:25:11.308
so we're using the same CSS selector,
but instead of saying the outline

00:25:11.391 --> 00:25:13.194
is transparent, I'm going to say--

00:25:14.442 --> 00:25:15.657
Give me one moment here.

00:25:15.658 --> 00:25:26.589
[silence]

00:25:26.590 --> 00:25:28.231
Sorry, I'm having some keyboard troubles.

00:25:28.870 --> 00:25:29.870
There we go.

00:25:30.189 --> 00:25:33.909
Instead of saying it should have
a transparent outline,

00:25:33.939 --> 00:25:36.399
I'm going to give it
a text decoration of underline,

00:25:36.669 --> 00:25:38.139
and then I will hit Publish.

00:25:39.181 --> 00:25:40.920
Now, let's go back and reload that page,

00:25:45.310 --> 00:25:49.230
and I'm going to try to again use
the tab key to navigate across this page.

00:25:59.141 --> 00:26:01.130
Let me make that a little bigger for you.

00:26:01.131 --> 00:26:02.559
I'll press Tab,

00:26:04.749 --> 00:26:07.599
and you can see the one comment control
does have a focus outline,

00:26:07.630 --> 00:26:08.679
and I'll press Tab again,

00:26:09.370 --> 00:26:13.947
and now you can see
that first tab control has an underline,

00:26:13.948 --> 00:26:15.909
so that indicates
that that has keyboard focus.

00:26:15.999 --> 00:26:17.019
If I press Tab again,

00:26:17.530 --> 00:26:20.710
the second tab control has an underline,
which means it has keyboard focus,

00:26:20.739 --> 00:26:21.910
so if I press Enter now,

00:26:23.049 --> 00:26:24.640
that'll change to the other tab.

00:26:25.297 --> 00:26:28.629
That's one way that you can fix
CSS-level issues with the plugin,

00:26:28.960 --> 00:26:35.710
find the specific CSS selector,
and then write a new style to override it.

00:26:42.159 --> 00:26:43.238
What if that doesn't work?

00:26:43.239 --> 00:26:46.600
What if you have what I would say is
a fundamentally inaccessible plugin?

00:26:47.559 --> 00:26:50.828
In that case, you got to reach out
to the plugin developer and file

00:26:50.829 --> 00:26:52.090
an accessibility bug.

00:26:52.749 --> 00:26:57.040
It is important that plugin developers
know that accessibility issues exist

00:26:57.188 --> 00:26:58.188
in their code,

00:26:58.329 --> 00:27:00.569
it's important that they know
that users care about that,

00:27:00.999 --> 00:27:03.099
and it's important
that they fix it for all users.

00:27:03.340 --> 00:27:06.229
Even if you're able to fix it
by changing the CSS,

00:27:06.460 --> 00:27:07.860
you might want to reach out anyway.

00:27:09.699 --> 00:27:12.670
It's also important to know
that a lot of plugin developers

00:27:13.570 --> 00:27:16.389
may not be full-time people
doing this as their job,

00:27:16.390 --> 00:27:18.969
it might be their side gig,
or for some people it might even be

00:27:18.970 --> 00:27:20.050
their unpaid hobby,

00:27:20.350 --> 00:27:24.699
so I would reach out and be very polite
and offer to work with them.

00:27:25.237 --> 00:27:27.158
Understand
that for some people it might take

00:27:27.159 --> 00:27:30.850
a little bit more time depending
on how much support is behind this plugin.

00:27:31.749 --> 00:27:36.189
I would also recommend that you describe
the real-world impacts to users

00:27:36.219 --> 00:27:39.010
so that the plugin developers
can understand how it affects people,

00:27:39.640 --> 00:27:41.888
and if it's important
to you, you can also describe

00:27:41.889 --> 00:27:44.919
how it impacts
your site's accessibility compliance.

00:27:46.449 --> 00:27:50.379
I would also recommend that you try
to be as descriptive as possible

00:27:50.679 --> 00:27:52.839
about both what the current issue is

00:27:53.830 --> 00:27:56.290
and how it could or should be fixed.

00:27:56.619 --> 00:27:59.110
Remember that if there's
accessibility issues in a plugin,

00:27:59.709 --> 00:28:02.349
you might know more about accessibility
than the plugin developer,

00:28:02.500 --> 00:28:04.140
so try to share that knowledge with them.

00:28:04.510 --> 00:28:06.578
Otherwise, if you just say,
"There's this problem,

00:28:06.579 --> 00:28:09.699
we need it fixed," they might not know
how to go about fixing it

00:28:09.789 --> 00:28:11.650
or what it would look like to fix it.

00:28:12.490 --> 00:28:14.919
Try to work with them,
be polite, be cooperative,

00:28:15.639 --> 00:28:19.719
read any documentation they have
about how to contact them and work

00:28:19.720 --> 00:28:20.720
from there.

00:28:21.460 --> 00:28:23.859
If for whatever reason
that's not going to work for you,

00:28:23.920 --> 00:28:26.520
if they don't get back to you,
if they're resistant to changing it

00:28:27.969 --> 00:28:30.429
that means you need to essentially find
a replacement plugin.

00:28:30.490 --> 00:28:34.449
Look for one that can fill the same need
on your site but doesn't have

00:28:34.450 --> 00:28:35.829
accessibility issues built in.

00:28:36.099 --> 00:28:38.485
Always be careful when you're switching

00:28:38.486 --> 00:28:40.418
to a new plugin or deciding
to use one on your site.

00:28:40.419 --> 00:28:42.939
I would recommend you always do
some accessibility testing to begin

00:28:42.940 --> 00:28:45.675
with before you become
really committed to it,

00:28:46.737 --> 00:28:49.659
but that's essentially
what you have to do,

00:28:49.690 --> 00:28:51.996
find a replacement
if it's not going to work.

00:28:51.997 --> 00:28:54.668
Now, I know some people
might be thinking, "I'm really attached

00:28:54.669 --> 00:28:55.909
to this one plugin we're using.

00:28:56.169 --> 00:28:58.599
The plugin developer isn't going
to work with us to fix it.

00:28:58.719 --> 00:29:00.068
I can't find a replacement.

00:29:00.069 --> 00:29:01.445
Is there anything I can do?"

00:29:01.446 --> 00:29:04.389
In that case, if you really need
to do something,

00:29:04.780 --> 00:29:08.498
or try to fix your plugin,
you can try to create

00:29:08.499 --> 00:29:13.947
a secondary plugin that will extend
the original plugin using custom hooks.

00:29:14.470 --> 00:29:18.639
Now, this will only work
if the developer of the original plugin

00:29:18.849 --> 00:29:22.568
created custom hooks
in that original plugin for you

00:29:22.569 --> 00:29:24.339
to essentially hook into and work with.

00:29:25.509 --> 00:29:28.599
If those custom hooks aren't
in that original plugin,

00:29:28.930 --> 00:29:31.629
you would then need
to modify your local version,

00:29:31.989 --> 00:29:36.309
add custom hooks, and then be able
to create that secondary plugin.

00:29:36.669 --> 00:29:38.529
If you're doing that,
I would recommend then you submit

00:29:38.530 --> 00:29:40.299
a patch to the original developer
and be like,

00:29:40.300 --> 00:29:42.788
"Can you please add
at least these custom hooks so that people

00:29:42.789 --> 00:29:44.919
can modify plugins?"

00:29:46.390 --> 00:29:48.848
You might be wondering, "Why
would I create a secondary plugin instead

00:29:48.849 --> 00:29:51.250
of just editing
the original plugin on my site?"

00:29:52.419 --> 00:29:57.100
That's because you should generally try
to avoid modifying a plugin directly,

00:29:57.370 --> 00:30:00.970
like the local version of a plugin
that you have installed on your site.

00:30:02.289 --> 00:30:04.929
That's because if you go ahead
and update that plugin,

00:30:05.469 --> 00:30:07.419
your changes will be overwritten.

00:30:07.599 --> 00:30:08.599
You will lose them.

00:30:09.339 --> 00:30:11.219
You might think, "Okay,
I just won't update it,"

00:30:11.349 --> 00:30:14.378
but if you do not update your plugin,
that means you're going to miss out

00:30:14.379 --> 00:30:16.479
on new features,
and you might even miss out

00:30:16.480 --> 00:30:17.799
on security patches,

00:30:17.800 --> 00:30:20.200
so that's not really
a good thing you're going to want to do.

00:30:21.399 --> 00:30:23.709
Again, if there is
an issue with your plugin,

00:30:24.009 --> 00:30:26.769
and you really want to fix it,
but the developer won't

00:30:27.729 --> 00:30:28.729
fix it,

00:30:28.870 --> 00:30:33.460
you can try to create the secondary plugin
that will hook into it using custom hooks.

00:30:34.000 --> 00:30:36.550
Sometimes this is referred to
as an add-on plugin,

00:30:38.109 --> 00:30:41.872
but here I'm going to note,
this is really quite advanced

00:30:41.873 --> 00:30:43.859
and really beyond
the scope of this presentation.

00:30:43.860 --> 00:30:46.288
I think you could probably do
a whole other presentation on this,

00:30:46.289 --> 00:30:48.119
so I look forward to watching that one.

00:30:48.419 --> 00:30:50.970
This is the part I have
the least experience with,

00:30:51.270 --> 00:30:53.429
and I will say, this
is pretty complicated stuff.

00:30:55.433 --> 00:30:58.378
You really want someone who's more
of a WordPress developer,

00:30:58.379 --> 00:31:00.900
who knows how to design
plugins to be able to do this.

00:31:01.446 --> 00:31:03.366
If you don't have someone
like that on your team,

00:31:03.630 --> 00:31:05.510
you're going to just have
to find a replacement,

00:31:05.699 --> 00:31:08.399
but if you really need an option,
this is something you can look into.

00:31:08.400 --> 00:31:11.819
At the end of this presentation, I'll have
a couple links to WordPress documentation

00:31:11.849 --> 00:31:14.323
on custom hooks that you can read

00:31:14.324 --> 00:31:17.219
to get a little bit better sense
of how that might work.

00:31:18.509 --> 00:31:21.450
My overall advice here, though,
is don't do this.

00:31:22.110 --> 00:31:23.849
If it's an accessibility issue
with a plugin,

00:31:23.850 --> 00:31:28.559
it really should be fixed at the core
so that it's fixed for everyone,

00:31:28.799 --> 00:31:30.352
all the different users of the plugin,

00:31:30.353 --> 00:31:32.159
and all the different users
of those sites.

00:31:32.700 --> 00:31:34.963
Also, this can be quite complicated.

00:31:35.730 --> 00:31:37.649
Try not to do this,
but if you really need to,

00:31:37.799 --> 00:31:39.343
it's something you can look into.

