00:33:31.650 --> 00:33:35.578
It's again light gray text
on a white background,

00:33:35.579 --> 00:33:36.579
so it's hard to see.

00:33:36.810 --> 00:33:38.699
This is something that's set
at the theme-level

00:33:38.700 --> 00:33:41.910
because it's part of a component
that's repeated across a lot of pages.

00:33:42.360 --> 00:33:44.969
If I were to go
to this Hello World post on my site

00:33:45.330 --> 00:33:49.589
and look at it just in the page view,
I wouldn't see that September date

00:33:49.590 --> 00:33:51.750
anywhere because it's part
of the metadata of the post.

00:33:52.274 --> 00:33:57.090
When your users actually visit the site
again that comes from the theme.

00:33:57.569 --> 00:34:00.644
This is an example of what I would say is
a theme-level issue.

00:34:01.754 --> 00:34:03.734
How could you fix it?

00:34:04.349 --> 00:34:07.335
First, with theme-level issues,
you have what I would call the easy way.

00:34:08.358 --> 00:34:09.358
You have two options here.

00:34:09.359 --> 00:34:13.709
The first is to go to the theme customizer
and look for relevant options

00:34:13.769 --> 00:34:17.699
and then adjust those as appropriate,
if you have any good options.

00:34:18.309 --> 00:34:20.369
If there are issues
in your sidebar or footer,

00:34:20.370 --> 00:34:22.589
in the theme customizer,
you can look under widgets

00:34:22.590 --> 00:34:26.579
and you might be able to edit
those using the WordPress block editor.

00:34:27.600 --> 00:34:29.820
Then again if there are CSS-level issues

00:34:30.420 --> 00:34:35.417
with your theme, you can again try adding
custom CSS in the additional CSS panel.

