00:35:35.098 --> 00:35:38.849
With some theme-level issues,
you can fix them just by coming

00:35:38.850 --> 00:35:43.379
to the customizer and exploring
the available options here and seeing

00:35:43.410 --> 00:35:44.519
what you're able to change.

00:35:44.549 --> 00:35:46.980
For some theme-level issues,
that'll do the trick,

00:35:47.219 --> 00:35:48.219
which is awesome.

00:35:48.629 --> 00:35:51.048
That is again
what I would call the easy way.

00:35:51.557 --> 00:35:56.609
Again, that will vary based on your theme
and what options it supports users

00:35:56.610 --> 00:35:58.398
to tweak with in that manner.

00:36:00.660 --> 00:36:01.660
What about the hard way?

00:36:02.489 --> 00:36:05.158
Again, you can reach out
to the theme developer and file

00:36:05.159 --> 00:36:06.209
an accessibility bug.

00:36:06.869 --> 00:36:08.998
Again, even if you're able to do it
the easy way,

00:36:08.999 --> 00:36:11.279
you might want to do this anyway
so that it can be fixed

00:36:11.280 --> 00:36:13.915
for all users of that theme
across multiple sites.

00:36:14.605 --> 00:36:17.279
A lot of what I said
about working with developers

00:36:17.849 --> 00:36:19.230
for plugins applies here.

00:36:19.529 --> 00:36:20.820
Be polite. Work with them.

00:36:20.879 --> 00:36:23.549
Be specific about the issue
and how it could be fixed.

00:36:24.809 --> 00:36:25.809
If that doesn't work,

00:36:25.949 --> 00:36:28.109
time again, you got
to switch from your theme

00:36:28.169 --> 00:36:30.660
to a different theme,
one that's more accessible.

00:36:31.200 --> 00:36:34.500
If you go to wordpress.org and look
in the theme repository there,

00:36:34.770 --> 00:36:36.359
there's a tag you should search for.

00:36:36.360 --> 00:36:39.587
It's called accessibility-ready.

00:36:39.959 --> 00:36:43.529
All of the themes that are marked
as accessibility-ready,

00:36:43.799 --> 00:36:46.740
have undergone
additional accessibility testing.

00:36:47.070 --> 00:36:49.770
Now, that doesn't guarantee
that they're perfect and flawless,

00:36:49.950 --> 00:36:52.980
but it means they've passed
a much higher bar of accessibility

00:36:53.040 --> 00:36:54.359
than most themes.

00:36:55.049 --> 00:36:57.298
If you're looking for a theme,
I would always suggest start

00:36:57.299 --> 00:36:58.738
with the accessibility-ready themes.

00:36:58.739 --> 00:37:01.740
Those ones are likely to have
the least amount of issues with them.

00:37:03.269 --> 00:37:06.119
Now, some of you again may be saying,
"I really like my theme,

00:37:06.239 --> 00:37:08.548
and my server won't fix it,
and I can't quite fix it

00:37:08.549 --> 00:37:10.829
the easy way, and I don't want
to switch to another one,

00:37:10.830 --> 00:37:11.830
what can I do?"

00:37:12.270 --> 00:37:17.160
In that case, you can create
a child theme to override

00:37:17.430 --> 00:37:19.980
the broken portions of your parent theme.

00:37:21.119 --> 00:37:24.210
Now, again why would you create
a child theme instead of just edit

00:37:24.269 --> 00:37:27.150
the local theme that you have
installed on your server?

00:37:27.810 --> 00:37:28.810
Similarly,

00:37:28.829 --> 00:37:33.750
if you edit that local version directly,
and then if you update your theme later,

00:37:34.140 --> 00:37:37.049
your changes will be overridden
and removed,

00:37:37.440 --> 00:37:40.109
which is not really a thing you want,
but with a child theme,

00:37:40.110 --> 00:37:41.110
if you set one up,

00:37:41.340 --> 00:37:45.628
and then if you update your theme later,
the parent theme,

00:37:46.198 --> 00:37:48.060
your edits will persist.

00:37:48.662 --> 00:37:50.908
That's the big perk
for using a child theme.

00:37:53.819 --> 00:37:56.520
Now, child themes are,
I would say, relatively easy

00:37:56.579 --> 00:38:00.883
to set up and start using,
but they can get quite complicated

00:38:00.884 --> 00:38:05.254
and require some major revisions
to the parent theme.

00:38:06.994 --> 00:38:08.369
Keep that in mind.

00:38:08.370 --> 00:38:10.799
If you're just making
a couple tweaks, it's not too hard.

00:38:10.830 --> 00:38:12.899
I would say it's more
of an intermediate-level thing,

00:38:12.900 --> 00:38:17.284
but if you're really making big changes,
then it can be more of an advanced task.

00:38:18.214 --> 00:38:21.839
Essentially, the way
the child theme works is you add a folder

00:38:21.869 --> 00:38:25.200
to your WordPress server where you store
your themes for your child theme.

00:38:25.499 --> 00:38:28.649
You have to set it up in a particular way,
but it's not too complicated.

00:38:29.189 --> 00:38:32.998
Then any files that you have
in your child theme folder will override

00:38:32.999 --> 00:38:35.335
the equivalent files for the parent theme.

00:38:35.725 --> 00:38:38.465
The one exception is
for your functions.php file,

00:38:38.520 --> 00:38:40.885
which will be added in addition to that.

00:38:41.335 --> 00:38:43.975
It'll be loaded immediately
before the parents.

00:38:45.390 --> 00:38:47.005
If you're setting up a child theme,

00:38:47.790 --> 00:38:51.118
what you can do is you can try
to identify the relevant attributes

00:38:51.119 --> 00:38:53.880
in the source code,
and then search for those,

00:38:53.900 --> 00:38:55.349
the source code of the parent theme.

00:38:55.709 --> 00:38:56.709
Search for those.

00:38:57.000 --> 00:38:58.769
Through trial and error,
you can figure out

00:38:58.770 --> 00:39:02.219
how to tweak the parent theme
to fix any issues you have with it

00:39:03.330 --> 00:39:07.229
and then you're
off to the races essentially.

00:39:07.980 --> 00:39:10.798
If you're doing a child theme,
I would highly suggest you set up

00:39:10.799 --> 00:39:16.079
a local WordPress environment
or a staging site where you can test out

00:39:16.080 --> 00:39:18.870
your changes before pushing them
to the production site

00:39:19.560 --> 00:39:21.568
because there might be
a bit of trial and error,

00:39:21.569 --> 00:39:23.906
and you could accidentally break
things in your theme

00:39:24.599 --> 00:39:27.240
before you figure out the correct changes
to make.

00:39:27.929 --> 00:39:29.489
Then, again,
when you're updating your theme,

00:39:29.490 --> 00:39:32.699
there's a chance things
could get broken again,

00:39:32.700 --> 00:39:36.179
and so if it's a bigger update,
more of a chance if it's a small update

00:39:36.180 --> 00:39:39.778
to the theme, it'll probably be okay,
but each time you update

00:39:39.779 --> 00:39:42.478
the theme, you might need to go back
and make some tweaks on your side

00:39:42.479 --> 00:39:43.479
to your child theme,

00:39:44.099 --> 00:39:46.890
and that's something you would want
to do in a local environment

00:39:47.009 --> 00:39:48.327
or on a staging site.

00:39:49.259 --> 00:39:51.446
How do you actually go
about finding that all?

