00:42:36.590 --> 00:42:37.639
at in this presentation,

00:42:38.359 --> 00:42:41.254
there's a lot of things
that go into a WordPress site,

00:42:41.255 --> 00:42:43.670
so you'd probably want
to look at, for example,

00:42:44.000 --> 00:42:49.158
like your theme might have a bug tracker,
and it might list accessibility issues

00:42:49.159 --> 00:42:50.104
with your theme,

00:42:50.105 --> 00:42:54.109
but that would be probably
in a different GitHub repository

00:42:54.110 --> 00:42:57.978
or code repository than the one
where accessibility issues

00:42:57.979 --> 00:42:59.689
for WordPress core are tracked,

00:43:00.800 --> 00:43:03.678
and so it's going to depend
on where the exact issue comes

00:43:03.679 --> 00:43:04.826
from ultimately.

00:43:05.606 --> 00:43:09.296
<v Laura> I think too, depending
on your level experience,

00:43:09.650 --> 00:43:15.859
I know that a bunch of us have done
presentations where the top five things,

00:43:16.070 --> 00:43:18.290
like those basic things of what to check,

00:43:18.799 --> 00:43:21.620
the contrast is one, like you pointed out,

00:43:22.519 --> 00:43:26.126
the font size and that
kind of thing, so yes,

00:43:26.389 --> 00:43:28.759
it depends on your level
of experience too,

00:43:28.760 --> 00:43:31.133
and you just got to learn
and build upon that too.

00:43:32.963 --> 00:43:34.613
All right, our next question.

00:43:34.969 --> 00:43:36.680
Is the text used

00:43:37.310 --> 00:43:39.260
an accessible font?

00:43:39.710 --> 00:43:40.818
How can we tell?

00:43:40.819 --> 00:43:44.723
Are there checks
to call out inaccessible fonts?

00:43:47.506 --> 00:43:48.676
<v Cam> Yes.

00:43:50.836 --> 00:43:53.135
In this case, I'm going to have to give
a shout out to Equalize Digital.

00:43:53.136 --> 00:43:57.258
They have a plugin that you can use
in a WordPress site.

00:43:57.259 --> 00:43:59.658
You install the plugin,
and it'll actually flag

00:43:59.659 --> 00:44:02.727
accessibility issues for you
through the WordPress interface.

00:44:03.709 --> 00:44:05.787
That's a good way to sort of quickly see

00:44:05.788 --> 00:44:09.085
what types of accessibility issues
you might have on your site.

00:44:09.086 --> 00:44:11.928
It might not catch everything,
but I think it's a pretty decent way

00:44:11.929 --> 00:44:13.936
to catch
at least some of the major issues.

00:44:15.362 --> 00:44:17.359
<v Laura> The next question is from Jen.

00:44:17.780 --> 00:44:21.530
Would it be redundant
to leave the image description

00:44:21.590 --> 00:44:26.851
in the description field and then
to add it to the alt text field?

00:44:27.550 --> 00:44:30.559
<v Cam> That's a good question.
I don't think it matters so much.

00:44:30.829 --> 00:44:33.259
My understanding is
that the issue description field,

00:44:33.799 --> 00:44:37.999
when you go to the media library
on your site is just for the back end

00:44:38.030 --> 00:44:41.988
so that you can have a note
about the image description.

00:44:41.989 --> 00:44:44.059
I don't think it gets presented
to users anywhere.

00:44:45.350 --> 00:44:49.279
It's a little redundant
and it just depends on how you're managing

00:44:49.280 --> 00:44:50.280
that on your site.

00:44:50.464 --> 00:44:53.358
Ultimately, the alternative text field
is the one that's most important

00:44:53.359 --> 00:44:54.424
for accessibility.

00:44:55.933 --> 00:44:59.593
<v Laura> To play on that,
the next question from Philippe,

00:45:00.620 --> 00:45:04.608
and this always comes up too,
is when to use that alt text.

00:45:04.609 --> 00:45:05.900
Our biggest discussion,

00:45:08.300 --> 00:45:13.219
in my understanding, this is
a decorative image as the blind person

00:45:13.220 --> 00:45:18.858
doesn't learn anything from the image,
doesn't need any information from it,

00:45:18.859 --> 00:45:21.033
so you were doing the bean image,

00:45:21.034 --> 00:45:23.614
is that correct?
<v Cam> Yes, yes.

00:45:25.205 --> 00:45:28.023
<v Laura> Is there an overall guideline?

00:45:28.310 --> 00:45:31.243
What are your thoughts
when you're doing a website?

00:45:31.933 --> 00:45:35.239
<v Cam> That one could honestly again be
its own presentation to dive

00:45:35.240 --> 00:45:38.839
into because it depends a lot,
but ultimately it's contextual,

00:45:38.840 --> 00:45:40.606
and some people are going
to have different views.

00:45:40.607 --> 00:45:43.969
The one I shared, I think arguably is
a bit more of a borderline case,

00:45:45.109 --> 00:45:48.469
but in this case,
as a sighted user who's looking

00:45:48.470 --> 00:45:52.158
at a recipe page, I'm definitely going
to want to see a picture of what the food

00:45:52.159 --> 00:45:54.948
looks like, so I think
it's reasonable to try to provide

00:45:54.949 --> 00:46:01.128
that equivalent experience
to non-sighted users.

00:46:01.129 --> 00:46:03.969
In this case, I probably could have done
a better job trying to describe

00:46:04.249 --> 00:46:05.810
what exactly those beans looked like.

00:46:06.440 --> 00:46:08.718
I think if we had
a better example of alt text in that case,

00:46:08.719 --> 00:46:11.049
it might be more clear of,
"Oh, yes, this is helpful."

00:46:12.519 --> 00:46:15.489
<v Laura> You do have people
that have minimal sight

00:46:16.522 --> 00:46:22.518
too, so they appreciate
when they can see parts of an image too.

00:46:22.519 --> 00:46:23.675
<v Cam> Yes.

00:46:23.676 --> 00:46:28.550
<v Laura> I go on the side of caution,
and I at least give something

00:46:28.850 --> 00:46:33.318
to an image
that might be considered decorative,

00:46:33.319 --> 00:46:38.149
unless it's being talked
about in the text too,

00:46:39.200 --> 00:46:41.929
then you're double upping on that.

00:46:42.889 --> 00:46:44.389
The next question is,

00:46:44.749 --> 00:46:48.568
can you talk
about the header hierarchy on a page?

00:46:49.750 --> 00:46:50.960
<v Cam> Yes, yes.

00:46:51.170 --> 00:46:54.049
There are six levels of heading,
headings one through six.

00:46:54.260 --> 00:46:57.079
Heading level one should be
the primary page heading.

00:46:57.680 --> 00:46:59.839
In WordPress, this is usually set up to be

00:47:00.530 --> 00:47:03.319
the name of a page or a post,

00:47:04.219 --> 00:47:07.279
then any headings under
that should be heading level two.

00:47:07.459 --> 00:47:09.169
If you have a subheading under
one of those,

00:47:09.170 --> 00:47:11.960
it should be three,
and so on and so forth.

00:47:12.740 --> 00:47:14.839
It's best to try to go in that order.
Headings

00:47:15.350 --> 00:47:17.600
start with one,
any subheadings under that are two.

00:47:17.960 --> 00:47:20.749
If you have a subheading,
it should be a heading level three,

00:47:20.780 --> 00:47:21.780
and so on.

00:47:23.237 --> 00:47:24.707
<v Laura> All right.
Thank you.

00:47:31.490 --> 00:47:38.411
From Roger, thoughts on using
.focus versus .focus-visible?

00:47:39.290 --> 00:47:40.010
<v Cam> That's a good question.

00:47:40.250 --> 00:47:46.789
The CSS pseudo selector for focus
will show whatever that focus style

00:47:46.790 --> 00:47:50.239
is anytime the element has focus,
which often typically includes

00:47:50.240 --> 00:47:53.467
when a sighted user clicks
on the element for a moment.

00:47:53.468 --> 00:47:57.088
Focus-visible, the CSS pseudo selector
focused as visible,

00:47:58.288 --> 00:48:02.060
your browser is going to try to guess
if you're a keyboard user or a mouse user,

00:48:02.330 --> 00:48:04.357
and so if you're a mouse user
and you click on it,

00:48:04.358 --> 00:48:05.600
it probably won't show.

00:48:07.220 --> 00:48:10.399
I tend to prefer just to use
the focus pseudo selector,

00:48:10.790 --> 00:48:13.220
and I like to design
beautiful focus states

00:48:13.280 --> 00:48:15.099
that are satisfying,

00:48:15.919 --> 00:48:19.629
but you can use focus-visible as well.

00:48:20.209 --> 00:48:21.739
It usually works pretty well.

00:48:21.770 --> 00:48:26.359
It sort of comes down to your design
and the site's vision.

00:48:27.060 --> 00:48:29.959
I think focus is great
because it is going to work for everyone,

00:48:30.019 --> 00:48:34.199
but I've seen the focus-visible one work,
and it can be acceptable as well.

00:48:36.419 --> 00:48:40.469
<v Laura> All right. The next question,
got about two more minutes.

00:48:42.019 --> 00:48:44.449
As awareness of accessibility issues
grows,

00:48:44.450 --> 00:48:48.050
particularly
due to the legal requirements as such,

00:48:50.000 --> 00:48:54.889
websites are indeed becoming more equipped
with built-in features that facilitate

00:48:54.890 --> 00:48:57.230
the creation of accessible sites.

00:48:57.709 --> 00:49:03.078
This trend is especially evident
in the government sector where Civic Plus

00:49:03.079 --> 00:49:05.929
has established itself
as a significant player.

00:49:06.230 --> 00:49:11.929
What do you think will happen, especially
since a lot of websites have to scale back

00:49:11.989 --> 00:49:13.730
on cool-looking sites?

00:49:14.059 --> 00:49:17.553
Do you think it will merge so cool design

00:49:17.554 --> 00:49:21.775
and just basic design
will be both by 2026?

00:49:22.975 --> 00:49:24.865
<v Cam> That is a huge question.

00:49:32.068 --> 00:49:36.019
I hope to see websites that are accessible
and beautiful and cool.

00:49:36.185 --> 00:49:38.448
I've definitely seen sites
that are both, and I don't think there's

00:49:38.449 --> 00:49:41.448
any reason you need to have
a very basic site in order

00:49:41.449 --> 00:49:42.449
to be accessible.

00:49:43.789 --> 00:49:46.008
I do think there's some design
out there that's over the top,

00:49:46.009 --> 00:49:47.869
and I think we might benefit
from a society

00:49:47.870 --> 00:49:50.569
from just more chill websites,

00:49:51.230 --> 00:49:54.200
but I don't think
there's necessarily any contrast

00:49:54.290 --> 00:49:58.908
or fight there between design
and accessibility.

00:50:00.019 --> 00:50:01.347
<v Laura> Yes, definitely.

00:50:01.348 --> 00:50:04.176
Equalize Digital, check out their website.

00:50:04.339 --> 00:50:08.448
They have a cool website that brings
in a lot of different colors and stuff

00:50:08.449 --> 00:50:10.576
like that, but still is accessible.

00:50:10.577 --> 00:50:13.429
That's one of them.

00:50:14.270 --> 00:50:15.349
Next question from Heather.

00:50:15.350 --> 00:50:22.458
Can anyone please share the--
Oh, sorry, anonymous,

00:50:22.459 --> 00:50:27.939
how to work with maps and coordinates
in XML markup and site issues?

00:50:32.559 --> 00:50:36.259
<v Cam> XML markup and maps,
again I feel like that could easily be

00:50:36.260 --> 00:50:38.390
